Content: 𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.

B.Choice: It illustrates the extent to which Mr. Skimpole is embarrassed about his past.

Content: Which quotation from the passage has a similar impact as the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “'Some pounds, odd shillings, and halfpence, I think, were mentioned.'” (paragraph 10)

B.Choice: “'I don't know what the business name of it may be, but I suppose there is some instrument within their power that would settle this?'” (paragraph 22)

Content: 𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.

B.Choice: He preoccupies himself with fanciful pursuits to avoid facing reality.

Content: Which quotation from the paragraph provides evidence for the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “'... that excellent sense and quiet habit of method and usefulness, which anybody must observe in you ...'” (paragraph 7)

B.Choice: “... had entirely washed his hands of the difficulty ...” (paragraph 21)

Content: 𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.
Select a central theme of the passage.

A.Choice: It is important to prepare in advance for potential challenges.

B.Choice: Different people can view particular situations in very different ways.

C.Choice: It is sometimes impossible to remain hopeful when confronting certain difficulties.

D.Choice: Those who truly enjoy music are able to share their pleasure with others.

Content: Select the 𝗧𝗪𝗢 most relevant details that support the theme.

A.Choice: “Mr. Skimpole could play on the piano and the violoncello, and he was a composer—had composed half an opera once, but got tired of it—and played what he composed with taste.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “I ventured to inquire, generally, before replying, what would happen if the money were not produced.” (paragraph 17)

C.Choice: “Richard and I looked at one another again. It was a most singular thing that the arrest was our embarrassment and not Mr. Skimpole's.” (paragraph 21)

D.Choice: “'Keep your temper, my good fellow, keep your temper!' Mr. Skimpole gently reasoned with him as he made a little drawing of his head on the fly-leaf of a book.” (paragraph 26)

E.Choice: “I had always thought that some accident might happen which would throw me suddenly, without any relation or any property, on the world and had always tried to keep some little money by me that I might not be quite penniless.” (paragraph 30)

F.Choice: “I think the reply was, 'Cut away, then!'” (paragraph 34)

𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.

Content: 𝗧𝗛𝗜𝗦 𝗤𝗨𝗘𝗦𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡 𝗛𝗔𝗦 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗣𝗔𝗥𝗧𝗦.
